# GitHub

## What is GitHub?

GitHub is a **cloud-based platform** that hosts Git repositories online. It allows developers to store, manage, share, and collaborate on projects using Git.

While **Git** is a Version Control System that works on your local computer, **GitHub** provides an online platform where repositories can be backed up, shared, and developed collaboratively.

GitHub is one of the most popular platforms used by software developers, companies, and open-source communities around the world.

---

# Why Use GitHub?

GitHub offers many benefits beyond Git itself.

It allows developers to:

- Store projects online.
- Back up code safely.
- Collaborate with team members.
- Contribute to open-source projects.
- Track bugs and issues.
- Review code before merging.
- Showcase projects through a public portfolio.

---

# How GitHub Works

GitHub works together with Git.

The general workflow is:

```text
Create Project
        │
        ▼
Local Repository (Git)
        │
        ▼
Commit Changes
        │
        ▼
Push
        │
        ▼
GitHub Repository
```

Developers can then:

- View code online.
- Download repositories.
- Make contributions.
- Review changes.
- Collaborate with others.

---

# What is a GitHub Repository?

A **GitHub Repository** is an online storage space for your project.

A repository contains:

- Source code
- Project files
- Commit history
- Branches
- Issues
- Pull Requests
- README files
- Licenses

Repositories can be:

- Public
- Private

---

# Public Repository

A **Public Repository** can be viewed by anyone.

Anyone can:

- Read the code.
- Clone the repository.
- Contribute (if permitted).

Public repositories are commonly used for:

- Open-source projects
- Learning
- Portfolio projects

---

# Private Repository

A **Private Repository** is only accessible to people who have permission.

Private repositories are commonly used for:

- Company projects
- Personal work
- Confidential software

---

# GitHub Features

GitHub provides many useful features.

## Repository

Stores your project and its complete history.

---

## Branch

A branch allows developers to work on new features without affecting the main code.

Example:

```
main
 │
 ├── login-feature
 │
 ├── payment-feature
 │
 └── bug-fix
```

---

## Fork

A **Fork** creates your own copy of someone else's repository.

You can:

- Experiment freely.
- Make changes independently.
- Submit improvements later.

Forking is widely used in open-source development.

---

## Clone

Cloning means downloading a complete copy of a GitHub repository to your local computer.

Example:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/username/project.git
```

---

## Pull Request (PR)

A **Pull Request** is a request to merge changes into another branch.

It allows maintainers to:

- Review code.
- Suggest improvements.
- Approve changes.
- Merge contributions.

Pull Requests are one of GitHub's most important collaboration features.

---

## Issues

GitHub Issues help track:

- Bugs
- Feature requests
- Improvements
- Tasks

They make project management easier.

---

## Stars

A **Star** is similar to bookmarking or liking a repository.

Developers use stars to:

- Save useful repositories.
- Show appreciation.
- Discover popular projects.

---

## Watch

Watching a repository allows you to receive notifications about:

- New commits
- Pull Requests
- Releases
- Discussions

---

## Releases

Releases are official versions of a project.

Example:

```
Version 1.0

Version 1.1

Version 2.0
```

They help users download stable versions of software.

---

## GitHub Pages

GitHub Pages allows you to host static websites directly from a GitHub repository.

It is commonly used for:

- Personal portfolios
- Documentation
- Project websites

---

## GitHub Actions

GitHub Actions is GitHub's automation platform.

It can automatically:

- Build projects
- Run tests
- Deploy applications
- Perform continuous integration (CI)

---

# Git vs GitHub

| Git | GitHub |
|------|---------|
| Version Control System | Cloud hosting platform |
| Installed locally | Accessible through a web browser |
| Tracks file changes | Hosts Git repositories |
| Works offline | Requires internet for collaboration |
| Manages project history | Enables sharing and collaboration |

---

# Common GitHub Workflow

```text
Create Repository
        │
        ▼
Clone Repository
        │
        ▼
Make Changes
        │
        ▼
Commit Changes
        │
        ▼
Push Changes
        │
        ▼
Open Pull Request (if collaborating)
        │
        ▼
Review & Merge
```

---

# Advantages of GitHub

GitHub provides many advantages:

- Free hosting for Git repositories.
- Easy collaboration.
- Secure cloud backup.
- Open-source community.
- Code review using Pull Requests.
- Project management tools.
- Portfolio creation.
- Integration with CI/CD tools.

---

# GitHub in Real Life

Imagine a group of students working on a college project.

Without GitHub:

- Everyone sends files through email or messaging apps.
- Different file versions become confusing.
- Work may be overwritten accidentally.

With GitHub:

- Everyone works on the same repository.
- Every change is tracked.
- Team members can review each other's work.
- The complete project history is preserved.

